Okay cool, so you have the tools to get better. If you're B-Anon, then to improve your drawing, let's focus on the very first facial sketch.
1. The head needs to be less like a balloon. Start with a slightly bigger circle and then carve that inward.
2. Another thing, give your snout a poligonal structure. Some people draw prisms or cylinders. I personally go for a sort of triangular prism with a dull point.
3. Make the ears larger. It's supposed to be cute, right? Look at how large the ears are on typical artwork posted here. Often more than half the length of the head.
(Look, I'm not the great at art either but it's easier for me to point out your weaknesses than you finding them yourself.)

Lastly, in the second park, I found Fang, and was greatly amused by her dialogue.

I know an enormous amount of work had to go into this, and I am amazed by what you've done here. If SDS is lurking this thread, thanks.

Ah. Some seafood has a relatively mild flavor, like, say, perch or pollack. Canned mackerel and sardines are a little stronger, but there are other flavors present that keep it from becoming overwhelming. I only tried lobster once. It was at a buffet, and maybe it had been under the heat lamps a while. It had such a strong fishy taste that I found it nauseating and inedible. I have read that it has to do with certain proteins that are unique to marine life, and the degree to which they break down and release certain amine compounds after the cells die, especially during cooking. Fish that isn't fresh has a very distinctive odor, which is not too different from fish that's really overcooked. Sardines, canned mackerel, and so on, have really really really strong fishy flavors because they're sealed in the can first, then they are carried on a conveyor belt into a machine that blasts them with live steam to cook everything all the way through, and then some, to destroy bacteria. Shellfish can produce these substances also if they're not really really fresh, or if they're overcooked. But here, have an example of a fish I'd like to eat.
